TRICHOMONOSIS, FELINE - SWITZERLAND
***********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Wed 26 Mar 2008
From: Bruno Gottstein <bruno.gottstein@ipa.unibe.ch>


Feline _Tritrichomonas foetus_ infection - Switzerland
---------------------------------------------------
_Tritrichomonas foetus_ is a notifiable parasitic infection in
cattle. Switzerland has a recorded absence of the parasite for more
than 10 years, the last case occurred in an imported bull in 1997. In
the cattle population, infection is venereally transmitted and causes
transient sterility in heifers, which will undergo self-cure. In
bulls, there are no clinical signs and the animals remain
persistently infected. Bulls to be used for artificial insemination
thus have to undergo appropriate quarantine investigations, including
in vitro and PCR (polymerase chain reaction) laboratory testing of
preputial wash fluid.

In cats, _T. foetus_ has been shown to cause chronic large bowel
diarrhea, initially described in the US and subsequently in the UK.
Affected animals are often pedigree cats, of young age and/or that
live in multi-cat households.

Between July 2007 and March 2008, the Small Animal Clinic and the
Institute of Parasitology of the University of Bern, Switzerland,
investigated feces from 61 native cats suffering from chronic
diarrhea. Methodically, an appropriate fecal sample was processed
with the InPouch-TF culture system (BioMed Diagnostics, Oregon, USA),
and flagellates morphologically identical to _Tritrichomonas foetus_
grew in 12 out of 61 samples. DNA-isolation and subsequent PCR for
the detection of _Tritrichomonas_ sp. upon genus-specific ribosomal
DNA sequences was performed with all 12 culture-positive specimens,
and all yielded PCR-positive findings. Subsequent sequence analyses
of the resulting PCR-product revealed _Tritrichomonas foetus_ DNA for
all cases.

To our knowledge, in Switzerland the occurrence and spread of _T.
foetus_ infection is new in cats. The risk and the potential impact
of the occurrence of _T. foetus_ in cats for the Swiss cattle
population need now to be analyzed and elucidated, respectively.

Bruno Gottstein, Caroline Frey, Iwan Burgener
Parasitology and Small Animal Clinics
Vetsuisse Faculty
University of Bern
CH-3001 Bern, Switzerland
<bruno.gottstein@ipa.unibe.ch>

